<h2>Grind Uniformity and Extraction</h2>

<p>
  The key metric for evaluating any grinder is its <strong>Particle Size Distribution (PSD)</strong>. A quality grinder produces a tight, unimodal distribution — most particles clustered near the target size, with minimal fines (ultra-fine particles) and boulders (oversized chunks).
</p>

<p>
  Why fines are a problem:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Fines have dramatically more surface area per gram than correctly-sized particles, so they extract in seconds — long before the rest of the grounds are done</li>
  <li>The result is simultaneous over-extraction (bitterness, astringency from fines) and under-extraction (sourness, flatness from coarser particles) in the same cup</li>
  <li>In pour over, excess fines clog the filter, slow the draw-down, and shift the entire extraction timeline unpredictably</li>
</ul>

<p>
  A grinder producing a <strong>unimodal distribution</strong> means all particles reach their optimal extraction point at roughly the same time — producing clean, complex, balanced flavor. This is the mechanical reason grinder quality correlates so directly with cup quality.
</p>

